main event: An unidentified object was sighted in Warren, Ohio in July 1947, traveling at speeds of 500-700 MPH and landing after taking a downward course of 300.
interesting points: The object was described as 8-14" in diameter and colored blue-white, with no known discovery of its origin.
Dr. Hynek's evaluations suggest various probabilities for different incidents, with some categorized as non-astronomical and lacking evident explanation.

Several incidents are deemed to have a high probability of being astronomical in nature, while others are suggested to have non-astronomical explanations such as balloons, kites, flares, and falling bodies.
The report encompasses a wide range of incidents, from those with fair or low probability to those where evidence offered suggests no explanation.
This sighting occurred just a few days after the initial UFO incident in Roswell, New Mexico, which adds to the historical significance of this report.
